There cannot be a simplo destructive Dilemma of this kind, as is shewn by Abp. Whately, Logic, b. ii. ch. 4. ἓ. 5.

The Dilemma is sometimes exhibited in another form, as a conditional syllogism, in which the consequent of the major promiscis disjunctive, and tho whole denied in the minor; e. g. “ If A is B, G is D, or E is F, or G is H; but neither O is D, or Ε is F, nor G is H; therefore A is not B.'' This form is given by Wallis, lib. iii. cap. 19.; as well as by Wolf and Kant. But it is a perversion of the Dilemma proper, and introduces no distinction whatever; being merely e common disjunctive syllogism, as is shewn by Wallis himself.
